        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Tracking support for non-ascii characters]]></title>
        <id>https://github.com/swicg/activitypub-webfinger/issues/29</id>
        <link href="https://github.com/swicg/activitypub-webfinger/issues/29"/>
        <updated>2025-10-07T19:54:51.000Z</updated>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<img src="https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/6770?u=85e683e6edf44982a2d847e6bb28c63a53fbc43e&v=4" width="64" height="64" alt=""/><br/><p dir="auto">One of the benefits of using Webfinger is that it's possible, at least in theory, to use non-ascii characters for usernames. Unfortunately, there are not a lot of services that support them -- at least according to our document.</p>
<p dir="auto">For the top human languages, only 3 primarily use only non-ASCII characters (English, Malaysian, Indonesian), for a total of about 500 million people. That means about 90% of humans use languages with non-Latin, or accented, character sets.</p>
<p dir="auto">We have an opportunity to let people in the global majority use their names or words in their own language as usernames.</p>
<p dir="auto">This is a huge win for making software that focuses on real people.</p>
<p dir="auto">I propose we start:</p>
<ul dir="auto">
<li>Working on proof-of-concept implementations that use non-ASCII characters in <code class="notranslate">preferredUsername</code>, <code class="notranslate">webfinger</code> and the Webfinger username (with percent hashes)</li>
<li>Report issues on major ActivityPub implementations to start the process of supporting non-ASCII characters in usernames</li>
<li>Track interoperability</li>
</ul>]]></content>
